APIs Introduction

An API is a tool that helps share data/information with anyone. APIs are frequently created by companies to allow developers to create software that allows users to interact with their services. Some are more complex than others, so for the purposes of this tutorial we will only use APIs that require no authentication.

The word API stands for Application Programming Interface. APIs are meant to be accessible regardless of the programming language used. The data can be accessed through a URL the same way you would access a website, but typically returns very light text in the JSON format, which we will have to then manipulate to a format that works better in R and Python which will look like a data table with rows and columns. APIs provide a way for anyone to interact with a service through code, which can be as simple as pulling some data, or more complex, for example to programmatically trigger a trade on a cryptocurrency exchange. APIs are used by a large number of entities for different purposes, for example the US government provides data that anyone can perform research on: https://www.data.gov/developers/apis (which we will not use in this tutorial because it requires the user to request a free API “key” to authenticate).

API Usage

Let’s start with a simple example relating to the TV show Game of Thrones. We can get information relating to the different houses by navigating to this url: https://www.anapioficeandfire.com/api/houses

The webpage is shown below:

In order to get this information into R or another programming language, we will need to perform a GET request to retrieve the data from the url above. We can use the httr (Wickham 2020) package and use the GET function to receive data from the API:

library(httr)
api_request <- GET("https://www.anapioficeandfire.com/api/houses")

Using a GET request we can retrieve the data that we are interested in. APIs also sometimes allow users to make POST requests which allows the user to send data to the service rather than receiving it. Doing a POST requires the user to be authenticated, so in this tutorial we will only be doing GET requests using public API endpoints. An endpoint being a url like the one we used above.

If we view the result of the GET request we made, we will see a summary of the results of the request rather than the results themselves:

api_request
## Response [https://www.anapioficeandfire.com/api/houses]
##   Date: 2021-06-22 23:41
##   Status: 200
##   Content-Type: application/json; charset=utf-8
##   Size: 7.11 kB

The result Status: 200 indicates our request was successful. If the request we made was not successful, we would get a different status code, and we could write the logic in our code accordingly to deal with these outcomes. See this link for a full list of typical status codes and what they would mean.

Because we are interested in the actual content of the request, we can use the function content() from the httr package on the API request we made and retrieve the text of the content:

# Get the data from the url
example_data <- content(api_request, as='text')
# show the data in its raw format (not yet usable)
example_data

In order to convert the data to a tabular format with rows and columns, we can use the jsonlite (Ooms 2020) package to easily convert the JSON format to a dataframe (the standard way of storing tabular data in R and what Python’s pandas uses) by using the fromJSON() function:

library(jsonlite)
# Convert from JSON to dataframe
example_data <- fromJSON(example_data)
# Show dataframe
example_data

Use the arrow in the top right of the table to view the rest of the columns.

This tutorial

From this point forward, the results shown are updated every time the tutorial is refreshed because the data provided by the API endpoints changes over time. The tutorial was last run on:

Sys.time()
## [1] "2021-06-22 17:41:02 MDT"

Example - GitHub Job Board API

The first example given used data that does not update over time, but in many cases APIs can be used to collect data that evolves over time. To illustrate this point, the example below shows the most recent jobs posted to the Remotive jobs board as of the moment this tutorial was launched. This website posts remote jobs and we can pull the latest 10 postings from their website as follows:

url <- "https://remotive.io/api/remote-jobs?limit=10"
# Get the data from the url and convert to dataframe
remotive_data <- fromJSON(content(GET(url), as='text'))
# Extract jobs table from the request
remotive_jobs <- remotive_data$jobs
# Show data
remotive_jobs

The results are limited to the most recent 10 jobs posted through the url slug ?limit=10.

To illustrate the point that the data refreshes over time, let’s just show the job name, when it was posted, and the url of the job posting.

select(remotive_jobs, publication_date, title, url)

When we are interested in a specific subset of the data, there are usually ways to modify the request to return the data we need. For example, rather than returning all job postings we could make a request to only get jobs with the category of software development. To do this, we can add the text &category=software-dev to the url of the API request to add this optional parameter:

# Modify the url for the API request for New York location
url <- paste0(url, "&category=software-dev")
# Get the data from the url and convert to dataframe
software_dev_jobs <- fromJSON(content(GET(url), as='text'))
# Extract jobs table from the request
software_dev_jobs <- software_dev_jobs$jobs
# Show data
software_dev_jobs

Use the arrow in the top right corner of the table above to see the content of the different columns. Let’s take a closer look at the field company_logo_url which contains the url address to the company logo associated with the job listing:

software_dev_jobs$company_logo_url
##  [1] "https://remotive.io/job/703818/logo" "https://remotive.io/job/703819/logo"
##  [3] "https://remotive.io/job/669488/logo" "https://remotive.io/job/666617/logo"
##  [5] "https://remotive.io/job/666620/logo" "https://remotive.io/job/732518/logo"
##  [7] "https://remotive.io/job/652199/logo" "https://remotive.io/job/280720/logo"
##  [9] "https://remotive.io/job/717564/logo" "https://remotive.io/job/577662/logo"

By making a request at this url, we can display the image. See the example below showing the first company logo of the data (if there is one):

include_graphics(software_dev_jobs$company_logo_url[[1]])

You can also navigate to the url for the job listing: https://remotive.io/job/703818/logo

Play around with the results of the API request we made. The example below returns the maximum value of the publication_date field, meaning the date and time the most recent job posting was created:

max(software_dev_jobs$publication_date)
# Show the logo of the 5th job listing
include_graphics(software_dev_jobs$company_logo[[5]])

Notice that on our end we do not need to worry about storing any information or creating any infrastructure, and we do not need to worry about the difficulties that may come with storing the data, we can simply access the information we want in a way that’s kind of like going to a website that just shows the current data when visited. Towards the end of this tutorial you will learn about a newer technology that is similar to APIs called GraphQL which not only allows the user to specify the subset of the data they want to retrieve, but also allows the user to specify which fields to return for the request. For example, if we were only interested in displaying the company logos for the job listings, rather than pulling all of the fields associated with the API request we could be more efficient and create a request that only gives the one field. Before learning how to connect to and use a GraphQL endpoint, move on to the next section to get more practice using regular APIs, this time in the context of collecting prices from the cryptocurrency markets.

Cryptocurrency Data Examples

Price of Bitcoin

There are several free APIs we can use to retrieve cryptocurrency prices.

As a first example, let’s get the latest price of Bitcoin according to the website coindesk.com from the url: https://api.coindesk.com/v1/bpi/currentprice.json

url <- "https://api.coindesk.com/v1/bpi/currentprice.json"
# Get the data from the url
bitcoin_price <- content(GET(url), as='text')
# Convert from JSON to dataframe
bitcoin_price <- fromJSON(bitcoin_price)

Now we can show the current price of Bitcoin in USD:

bitcoin_price$bpi$USD$rate
## [1] "32,310.3593"

And when the price was last updated:

bitcoin_price$time$updated
## [1] "Jun 22, 2021 23:40:00 UTC"

HitBTC Exchange

The price we showed for Bitcoin is a simplified way of thinking of the price of a cryptocurrency and was the average price across many exchanges. In reality though, the market on an individual exchange is more complicated than a single price, and is instead made up of constantly evolving orders of people who are looking to buy and people who are looking to sell. Users submit their orders to the order book and the exchange takes care of filling orders matching buyers and sellers based on their designated price. We can use the API for the HitBTC exchange to return the 100 most favorable prices on each side of the current order book for Bitcoin (using the BTC/USD trading pair):

url <- "https://api.hitbtc.com/api/2/public/orderbook/BTCUSD"
# Get the data from the url
orderbook <- content(GET(url), as='text')
# Convert from JSON to dataframe
orderbook <- fromJSON(orderbook)
# Show the new data
orderbook

The ask column gives the current 100 open orders with the lowest asking price, meaning these orders are waiting for someone to purchase the cryptocurrency at the given price point:

orderbook$ask

The bid price is always going to be lower than orders on the ask side of the orderbook, because the second someone tries to purchase the cryptocurrency at a price that is higher than the lowest ask price, the bid order will immediately be filled:

orderbook$bid

We can think of the intersection between the ask and the bid prices available on the orderbook as the current price. Going back to the example from earlier with Bitcoin’s price, we have now seen that this is a bit of a construct because the price of Bitcoin not only depends on the individual exchange, but in practice there is a difference between the price you can purchase Bitcoin at and the price you can sell it for. Because Bitcoin has a large amount of liquidity, this difference tends to be intangible, but if trading other cryptocurrencies with less volume, this can become a meaningful difference.

Answer below:

Use the code below to change the cryptocurrency price you want to return and make a new API request. For example, you could modify the code to run for the “BTC” cryptocurrency instead of “ETH” and run the code again (see hint):

# Change the cryptocurrency you want to return prices for:
cryptocurrency <- "ETH"

# Build the url for the API request:
url <- paste0("https://api.hitbtc.com/api/2/public/orderbook/",cryptocurrency,"USD")

# Get the data from the url
orderbook <- content(GET(url), as='text')

# Convert from JSON to dataframe
orderbook <- fromJSON(orderbook)

# Show the lowest `ask` price at which we could purchase the cryptocurrency:
orderbook$ask
# Change the cryptocurrency you want to return prices for:
cryptocurrency <- "BTC"
# Build the url for the API request
url <- paste0("https://api.hitbtc.com/api/2/public/orderbook/",cryptocurrency,"USD")
# Get the data from the url
orderbook <- content(GET(url), as='text')
# Convert from JSON to dataframe
orderbook <- fromJSON(orderbook)
# Show the highest `bid` price at which we could sell the cryptocurrency:
orderbook$bid

GraphQL

In all of the previous examples we made specific requests to different URLs to return some data. When making the request, if we are only interested in returning one field, for example only the company logo from the GitHub job board, we would have to request a lot of redundant information to get to the single piece of information that we are interested in.

GraphQL helps solve this problem, and allows for a company/entity to provide an API where the user is able to specify the specific fields they want to return when making their API request, which, depending on the specific situation, can be much more efficient for both the developer of the API and the user.

GraphQL Example

The company SpaceX offers a public GraphQL endpoint: https://api.spacex.land/graphql/ - embedded below:

Rather than making requests to multiple API endpoints and manipulating the data to create the dataset that is needed, GraphQL gives the user a lot more flexibility and precision for the data to return. In the link embedded above, you can use the Explorer on the left side of the page and use the checkboxes to decide which endpoints and columns from those endpoints to include. The middle section displays the code to use to make the GraphQL request based on the selections made. Once the play button is clicked, the query is executed and the latest results are displayed on the right side of the page. We can use the query created and displayed in the middle section of the page to create the same request using R.

First, we will import the package ghql which will allow us to interact with a GraphQL endpoint:

# GraphQL R client: https://github.com/ropensci/ghql
library(ghql)

Next, we want to establish a connection with the GraphQL endpoint made available by SpaceX that was embedded above:

con <- GraphqlClient$new(
  url = "https://api.spacex.land/graphql/"
)

Now we can send a query to the GraphQL endpoint using the example given at https://api.spacex.land/graphql/

First we need to create a new object with an empty query:

graphql_request <- Query$new()

Now we can build the request:

graphql_request$query('mydata', '{
  launchesPast(order: "launch_date_local") {
    mission_name
    launch_date_local
    links {
      article_link
      video_link
    }
  }
}')

Finally we can execute the query using con$exec() on the request we built above and assign the results to the spacex_data object:

spacex_data <- con$exec(graphql_request$queries$mydata)

Now that we have the results from the request, it will once again be in the JSON format, so like before we can convert the JSON format to a dataframe using the fromJSON function from the jsonlite package:

spacex_data <- fromJSON(spacex_data)

The data we retrieved this time has a strange nested structure, where we have a column like links which currently contains both the article_link and video_link columns. Because of this, the fromJSON function will return a list object instead of the expected dataframe. We can clean this up into a workable format by first using the as_tibble() function to convert the list to a tibble (which has similar properties to a dataframe, find out more here), and using the unnest() function on the new result:

spacex_data <- unnest(as_tibble(spacex_data))
# Show data:
spacex_data

We can programmatically show the video associated with the first row from the dataset:

include_graphics(spacex_data$links$video_link[[1]])

“the graph” (GRT)

In the next section we will talk about how to leverage GraphQL to interact with “The Graph Network,” which allows us to interact with networks built on the Ethereum blockchain and IPFS.

“the graph” - GRT

There are a large number of applications built on Ethereum (most being “dapps,” meaning decentralized applications), and because they are public blockchains, “the graph” project created a way for developers to make “subgraphs” that allow users to query data from smart contracts on the Ethereum blockchain through GraphQL.

For example, a vibrant virtual world owned by its users is being built on the “Decentraland” blockchain, and we can query information relating to things like real estate transactions using the Decentraland subgraph made available by the graph network:

https://thegraph.com/explorer/subgraph/decentraland/marketplace

Decentraland Subgraph Request

Why would we want to request any data from these services in the first place? As mentioned above, users can buy and sell digital real estate on Decentraland. We have been collecting data relating to these real-estate markets [TODO - ADD HERE]

First, we need to initialize the connection to the GraphQL endpoint as outlined in the documentation above:

con <- GraphqlClient$new(
  url = "https://api.thegraph.com/subgraphs/name/decentraland/marketplace"
)

Now we can use the default example from the page above and make the GraphQL request through R.

First we need to initialize an empty query:

qry <- Query$new()

Now we can run the same query used as the default example on thegraph’s website:

# Example Query
qry$query('mydata', '{
  orders(orderBy: createdAt, orderDirection: desc, first: 1000) {
    category
    txHash
    blockNumber
    nft {
      owner {
        address
        mana
      }
      image
      parcel {
        x
        y
      }
      estate{
        size
      }
    }
    nftAddress
    buyer
    price
    status
    createdAt
  }
}')

Now we can run the query and store the results in the object decentraland_orders and convert it as needed in the same ways we have done up to this point for results from API requests:

# Run query and convert results from JSON to a dataframe
decentraland_orders <- fromJSON(con$exec(qry$queries$mydata))
# Convert to tibble and unnest the data
decentraland_orders <- unnest(as_tibble(decentraland_orders))

Now we can view the results from the request:

decentraland_orders

Historical Data

The query we just performed above shows the current latest data that matches our request. Only having a single snapshot in time limits the analysis we are able to perform, so from this point forward we will instead use a dataset that gets pulled using GraphQL exactly as shown above where new results get appended every 12 hours using the pins package:

library(pins)
# Register the board to pull the data from
board_register(name = "pins_board", 
               url = "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/predictcrypto/pins/master/", 
               board = "datatxt")
# Pull the data "decentraland_market"
decentraland_data <- pin_get(name = "decentraland_market")
# Only keep unique data
decentraland_data <-  decentraland_data[!duplicated(decentraland_data[,c("blockNumber", "buyer", "category", "createdAt", 
                                                   "nftAddress", "txHash", "nft_owner_address", 
                                                   "nft_owner_mana", "parcel_x_coordinate", "parcel_y_coordinate")]),]
# Show the data 
decentraland_data

The field createdAt contains the unix timestamp of when the specific event took place on the Decentraland blockchain. We can convert the number to a proper date-time object several different ways, but one simple option is to use the anytime package, which will automatically detect the format and properly convert the column to the correct data type. After importing the package we can use the anytime() function on the createdAt column, making sure to convert the original value from a string to a number first:

library(anytime)
decentraland_data$createdAt <- anytime(as.numeric(decentraland_data$createdAt))

Now we can arrange the data from the latest data to the oldest using the arrange function and show the data again:

decentraland_data <- arrange(decentraland_data, desc(createdAt))
# Show the data
decentraland_data

We can view the contents of the nft_image and display the image:

include_graphics(decentraland_data[!is.na(decentraland_data$nft_image),]$nft_image[[1]])

The interaction with the smart contract, both when posting an item for sale and buying an item, is associated with a transaction on the Decentraland blockchain. The easiest way to view it, is by looking it up on the website etherscan.io. here is the link for the first:

paste0('https://etherscan.io/tx/',decentraland_data[!is.na(decentraland_data$txHash),]$txHash[[1]])
## [1] "https://etherscan.io/tx/0xb4feb2d72bcccd59b8082a07ae29b11d163b540c12e63cdd27e1b8758453aacd"

https://etherscan.io/tx/0xb4feb2d72bcccd59b8082a07ae29b11d163b540c12e63cdd27e1b8758453aacd

Before answering more concrete questions using the historical data, we should also make sure to only include transactions relating to someone actually making a purchase, rather than the land/item simply being posted for sale, as the results could easily be skewed by items listed for prices that are much higher than anyone would realistically pay. We can do this by identifying rows where we have an address for the column buyer, but even easier than that is to filter results with the status of sold:

decentraland_data <- filter(decentraland_data, status == 'sold')

Let’s also remove duplicates

decentraland_data <- distinct(decentraland_data, txHash, status, .keep_all = TRUE)

The two filtering operations above caused the data to go from 14494 rows to 1790 rows.

decentraland_data

Answering Questions About the Data

Let’s start by answering some questions relating to the data by comparing the results by the category field. First, let’s group the data by the field:

# group data by category
data_by_category <- group_by(decentraland_data, category)

How many records are there by category?

count(data_by_category)

Now we can calculate the average price by category:

summarise(data_by_category, avg_price_mana = mean(price_mana))

But what does the category even mean?

  • parcel - A single piece of real estate is called a parcel
  • estate - Multiple parcels adjacent to each other can be combined together to create a larger estate
  • wearable - An accessory that can be worn by users inside the Decentraland game
  • ens - ens stands for Ethereum Name Service which works a little bit like a domain name, but for the address of an Ethereum wallet. Within Decentraland, users can trade unique names for their characters and no two users/characters can have the same name at the same time because of the way the Ethereum Name Service works.

Visualizations

Next let’s visualize the data. First we need to import the ggplot2 package:

library(ggplot2)

Now we can plot the prices by category using a bar plot:

ggplot(summarise(data_by_category, avg_price_mana = mean(price_mana)), 
       aes(x=category, y=avg_price_mana)) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity")

Let’s make a box-plot instead, and make the y-axis a logarithmic scale so it is easier to visually compare the categories:

decentraland_boxplot <- ggplot(decentraland_data, aes(x=category, y=price_mana, color=category)) +
                          geom_boxplot() +
                          scale_y_log10()
# Show the boxplot
decentraland_boxplot

We can add new elements to the decentraland_boxplot chart to make changes to the visual comparison:

decentraland_boxplot + geom_jitter(position=position_jitter(0.2))

How are prices trending over time?

We can check how the average prices are evolving over time.

First let’s group the data by the date the transaction was made (UTC timezone), and get the average price by day for each category. We can use the mutate function from the dplyr package to add a new column for the day the transaction was made by extracting the string from the 1st element to the 10th element to only grab the date and convert it using anytime() before assigning the results to the new column createdAtDay:

decentraland_data <- mutate(decentraland_data, 
                            createdAtDay = anytime(substr(createdAt, 1, 10)))

Now we can group the data by the createdAtDay we just created and the category:

daily_prices <- group_by(decentraland_data, 
                         createdAtDay, 
                         category)

Now when we apply an operation like count() we get the results back by the groupings we specified above:

count(daily_prices)

Next let’s create the new R object daily_prices_averaged with the average price (in MANA) by day and category:

daily_prices_averaged <- summarise(daily_prices, 
                                   avg_price_mana = mean(price_mana),
                                   sum_price_mana = sum(price_mana))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'createdAtDay'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.

Finally we can visualize the results over time by category:

ggplot(daily_prices_averaged, aes(x=createdAtDay, y=avg_price_mana, color=category)) + geom_line()

And we can compare that to the total sum of MANA traded through the transactions by category:

ggplot(daily_prices_averaged, aes(x=createdAtDay, y=sum_price_mana, color=category)) + 
  geom_line() +
  scale_y_log10()

Now we can join the two data sources on the pkDummy field:

decentraland_data <- left_join(decentraland_data, 
                               mana_historical, 
                               by = 'pkDummy')

Now the dataframe decentraland_data should have the same number of rows as before, but include additional columns that allow us to calculate the correct value in terms of USD ($) at the time the transaction was made on the MANA blockchain.

We can use the bid_1_price, which indicates the best rate someone was willing to pay for MANA at the time the transaction was made (on the HitBTC exchange) to calculate the value_usd as the equivalent USD value of the MANA traded at the time:

decentraland_data <- mutate(decentraland_data, 
                            value_usd = bid_1_price * price_mana)

Now we can once again summarize the data and create visualizations showing the trend in terms of actual $ being traded in the Decentraland virtual real estate markets. First the data preparation steps repeated for the analysis at the daily level:

# Group the data
daily_prices <- group_by(decentraland_data, 
                         createdAtDay, 
                         category)
# Compute average and sum
daily_prices_averaged <- summarise(daily_prices, 
                                   avg_value_usd = mean(value_usd),
                                   sum_value_usd = sum(value_usd))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'createdAtDay'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.

Now we can visualize the trends in terms of USD ($) value (with a logarithmic y-axis scale to make the comparison easier):

ggplot(daily_prices_averaged, 
       aes(x=createdAtDay, y=avg_value_usd, color=category)) + 
  # Add lines
  geom_line() +
  # Make y-axis scale logarithmic
  scale_y_log10()

And the total USD ($) value being traded (with a logarithmic y-axis scale to make the comparison easier):

ggplot(daily_prices_averaged, 
       aes(x=createdAtDay, y=sum_value_usd, color=category)) + 
  # Add lines
  geom_line() +
  # Make y-axis scale logarithmic

Overall, since the earliest data was collected on the date 2021-01-26, we have been able to measure a USD ($) traded value of: $6,372,456. That is an average of $43,947.97 per day. Breakdown by day below:

avg_value_daily <- summarise(daily_prices_averaged, 
                             sum_value_usd = sum(sum_value_usd))
# Show the data
avg_value_daily

We can visualize the cumulative total value ($) over time by visualizing the data and using the cumsum() function on sum_value_usd for the cumulative value ($) over time:

# Make cumulative value chart
ggplot(avg_value_daily, aes(x=createdAtDay, y=cumsum(sum_value_usd))) +
  geom_line() +
  # Format y-axis to show formatted $
  scale_y_continuous(labels=dollar_format()) +
  # Adjust y-axis label
  ylab('Cumulative Value ($) of Transactions') +
  # Add title
  ggtitle('Cumulative value ($) of transactions in Decentraland', 
          subtitle = glue('Since: {min(avg_value_daily$createdAtDay)}, through: {max(avg_value_daily$createdAtDay)}'))

Specific Analysis

See this article for a better understanding of the way different pieces of land (parcels) are priced based on their location: https://medium.com/nonfungible/short-analysis-of-decentralands-uprising-economy-1e55ac687c35

Which provides a really great visual breakdown on the full Decentraland map:

It is really easy to tell that there are major differences in the price of land in Decentraland based on the location of the property. The main driver being how close the property is to the center of the map, where all players are teleported to when they start the game.

Meaning, we should be able to predict the value of a piece of land pretty accurately based on its location. Therefore, we will create a new variable distance_center to describe the combined distance of the x and y coordinates from the center of the map (coordinates 0,0). After that, we will also create a new column district based on the specific range of the coordinates, matching the breakdown of what is shown in the image above.
